<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="88" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="88">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="88">Pygofer with caudoventral processes short, covered with short spines, adjacent to base of caudodorsal processes; aedeagus somewhat tubular, bent at midlength in lateral aspect, apex asymmetrically bifurcate, gonopore apical on ventral surface between bifurcations, dorsal connective absent; style much longer than aedeagus, tapered to acute apex; subgenital plate with dense setae.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="88" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="88">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="88">Measurements. Male. Body length 7.59 mm; crown length 0.65 mm; width between eyes 0.84 mm; eye width 0.68 mm; clypeus length 1.52 mm; clypellus length 0.83 mm; pronotum length 0.74 mm; mesonotum + scutellum length 1.00 mm. Female unknown. External morphology and male genitalia as described in generic diagnosis.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="88" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="88">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="88">The species epithet is derived from the Latin word geniculus, referring to the aedeagus being geniculate or bent medially in lateral view.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
